9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 191, L.D. 458, “An Act to Improve Court
10 Procedure and Update Family Law”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act Regarding the Domestic Violence Advocate Privilege'
13 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
14 following:
15 'Sec. 1. 14 MRSA §6001, sub-§6, ¶H, as amended by PL 2017, c. 455, §3, is
16 further amended by amending subparagraph (1) to read:
17 (1) A statement signed by a Maine-based sexual assault counselor as defined in
18 Title 16, section 53‑A, subsection 1, paragraph B, an a domestic violence advocate
19 as defined in Title 16, section 53‑B, subsection 1, paragraph A A-4 or a victim
20 witness advocate as defined in Title 16, section 53‑C, subsection 1, paragraph C;
21 Sec. 2. 16 MRSA §53-B, as amended by PL 2013, c. 478, §§3 to 6 and c. 588, Pt.
22 E, §10, is further amended by amending the section headnote to read:
23 §53-B. Privileged communications to victim domestic violence advocate; family
24 violence
25 Sec. 3. 16 MRSA §53-B, sub-§1, as amended by PL 2013, c. 478, §§3 to 5, is
26 further amended to read:
27 1. Definitions. As used in this section, unless the context otherwise indicates, the
28 following terms have the following meanings.
29 A. "Advocate" means an employee of or volunteer for a nongovernmental or Maine
30 tribal program for victims of domestic or family violence who:
31 (1) Has undergone at least 30 hours of training; and
Page 1 - 132LR1559(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 191, L.D. 458
1 (2) As a primary function with the program gives advice to, counsels or assists
2 victims, supervises employees or volunteers who perform that function or
3 administers the program.
4 A-1. "Confidential communications" means all information, whether written or oral,
5 transmitted between a victim and a domestic violence advocate in the course of the
6 working relationship. "Confidential communications" includes, but is not limited to,
7 information received or given by the domestic violence advocate in the course of the
8 working relationship, advice, records, reports, notes, memoranda, working papers,
9 electronic communications, case files, history and statistical data, including name, date
10 of birth and social security number, that personally identify the victim.
11 A-2. "Confidential criminal history record information" has the same meaning as in
12 section 703, subsection 2.
13 A-3. "Criminal justice agency" has the same meaning as in section 703, subsection 4.
14 A-4. "Domestic violence advocate" means an employee of or volunteer for a domestic
15 violence services provider who has undergone at least 40 hours of training from a
16 domestic violence services provider that, at a minimum, includes:
17 (1) State and federal laws, rules and regulations on confidentiality and other
18 protections for victims of domestic violence;
19 (2) Mandated reporting;
20 (3) Civil and criminal legal processes in the State;
21 (4) Advocacy skills; and
22 (5) Local resources available for victims of domestic violence.
23 A-5. "Domestic violence services provider" means a private, nonprofit or tribal
24 organization that has as a primary function to provide services for and assistance to
25 victims of domestic violence through crisis intervention, safety planning, legal
26 information and educational information pertaining to domestic violence.
27 B. "Victim" means a victim of domestic or family violence.
28 Sec. 4. 16 MRSA §53-B, sub-§1-A, as amended by PL 2013, c. 588, Pt. E, §10, is
29 further amended to read:
30 1-A. Confidential criminal history record information. A Maine criminal justice
31 agency, whether directly or through any intermediary, may disseminate confidential
32 criminal history record information to an a domestic violence advocate for the purpose of
33 planning for the safety of a victim of domestic violence. An A domestic violence advocate
34 who receives confidential criminal history record information pursuant to this subsection
35 shall use it solely for the purpose authorized by this subsection and may not further
36 disseminate the information.
37 Sec. 5. 16 MRSA §53-B, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 1995, c. 128, §1, is amended to
38 read:
39 2. Privileged communication. Communications are privileged from disclosure as
40 follows.
Page 2 - 132LR1559(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 191, L.D. 458
1 A. A victim may refuse to disclose and may deny permission to an a domestic violence
2 advocate to disclose confidential written or oral communications between the victim
3 and the domestic violence advocate and written records, notes, memoranda or reports
4 concerning the victim.
5 B. Except as provided in subsection 3, a victim, domestic violence advocate or
6 domestic violence advocate's agency may not be required through oral or written
7 testimony or through production of documents to disclose to a court in criminal or civil
8 proceedings or to any other agency or person confidential communications between
9 the victim and the domestic violence advocate.
10 Sec. 6. 16 MRSA §806, sub-§4, as enacted by PL 2015, c. 411, §2, is amended to
11 read:
12 4. A counselor or advocate. A sexual assault counselor, as defined in section 53‑A,
13 subsection 1, paragraph B, or an a domestic violence advocate, as defined in section 53‑B,
14 subsection 1, paragraph A A-4. A person to whom intelligence and investigative record
15 information is disclosed pursuant to this subsection:
16 A. May use the information only for planning for the safety of the victim of a sexual
17 assault or domestic or family violence incident to which the information relates;
18 B. May not further disseminate the information;
19 C. Shall ensure that physical copies of the information are securely stored and remain
20 confidential;
21 D. Shall destroy all physical copies of the information within 30 days after their
22 receipt;
23 E. Shall permit criminal justice agencies providing such information to perform
24 reasonable and appropriate audits to ensure that all physical copies of information
25 obtained pursuant to this subsection are maintained in accordance with this subsection;
26 and
27 F. Shall indemnify and hold harmless criminal justice agencies providing information
28 pursuant to this subsection with respect to any litigation that may result from the
29 provision of the information to the person.
30 Sec. 7. 17-A MRSA §2109, sub-§2, as enacted by PL 2019, c. 113, Pt. A, §2, is
31 amended to read:
32 2. To domestic violence advocate. Communications by a victim, as defined in Title
33 16, section 53‑B, subsection 1, paragraph B, to an a domestic violence advocate, as defined
34 in Title 16, section 53‑B, subsection 1, paragraph A A-4, are privileged from disclosure as
35 provided in Title 16, section 53‑B, subsection 2, subject to exceptions in Title 16, section
36 53‑B, subsection 3.'
37 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
38 number to read consecutively.
39 SUMMARY
4400 This amendment replaces the bill, which is a concept draft, and changes the title. The
4411 amendment modifies the statute governing privileged communications between victims of
